	 Milan: Italy captain Fabio Cannavaro has asked Francesco Totti and Alessandro Nesta to end their international retirements and return for the Azzurri at next years World Cup. The AS Roma striker and AC Milan defender both quit after Italys 2006 World Cup triumph in Berlin but have been in good form after recovering from career-threatening injuries.   
	India lose
    Pune: India lost 37-108 against China in the first FIBA Asia U-16 Girls rsquo; meet Tuesday.      
	New Delhi: India will spend an estimated Rs 10,555 crore in hosting next years Commonwealth Games and the Organising Committee for the Games would generate a revenue of around Rs 1,708 crore, the government said Tuesday.             
	 San Antonio: San Antonio Silver Stars coach Dan Hughes confirmed Monday that disgraced track star Marion Jones has been training with his assistants to possibly play in the WNBA, more than a year after the 34-year-old was released from federal prison for lying about doping.        
	Durban: South Africa fast bowler Dale Steyn could miss the fifth and final one-dayer against England on Friday due to a hamstring injury. Steyn was hurt in the third match and sat out the fourth game which England won by seven wickets to take a 2-1 series lead.         
	 Karachi: The Pakistan foreign ministry has no objection in allowing the countrys cricketers from playing in the IPLs third edition next year in India and, if the interior ministry gives a security clearance, the players will be issued NOCs soon, a sports ministry spokesperson said Tuesday.        
	 New Delhi: The Indian Cricket League could be dragged to court by disgruntled players who have not been paid their fees amounting to millions of dollars. FICA chief executive Tim May said that the players, including eight from Australia, were mulling legal action.      
	Hodge move  
	Melbourne: Former Australia and Kolkata Knight Riders batsman Brad Hodge Tuesday announced he will retire from first class cricket at the end of this year. Hodge, 35, will end his 17-year first-class careerplaying in Victoria states next two matches in Australias domestic Sheffield Shield competition. He will then retire as the states leading first-class run-scorer, but will continue to play for its T20 and limited-overs teams.                                                                                                                                                  
